        "description": {
            "name": "description",
            "type": "java.lang.String",
            "value": "I encountered a bit of a strange\/unexpected behaviour when using Zend_Form_Element, a textarea specifically. Text was assigned to the element and saved into the database (UTF-8). That worked fine. Default encoding for Zend_View seems to be UTF-8 whereas my HTML document's encoding is ISO-8859-1. Form element decorator used the view object (with encoding set to UTF-8) to render a text area, however, this resulted to an empty textarea with no value displayed whatsoever. It appears that the text entered into the text area was not encoded in UTF-8 and htmlspecialchars [1] silently dropped the whole string as some\/all of the characters were not UTF-8 encoded.\r\n\r\nWould it be possible to raise an exception (or another type of error event) when encoding of the string does not match the encoding specified in view?\r\n\r\n[1] http:\/\/www.php.net\/manual\/en\/function.htmlspecialchars.php#93620"
        },
